{
  "answer": "**No works in the corpus explicitly reflect on the \"dignity of the body.\"** Searches for phrases like \"dignity of the body,\" \"dignity of body,\" and related terms yielded no results. \"Dignity\" (*dignité*) appears frequently in the French political-economic texts of Charles Dunoyer and Charles Comte, but always in contexts of moral, social, or personal honor (e.g., labor's role in elevating human dignity), untied to the physical body itself.[^1][^2]\n\nHowever, several works contain **reflections on the indignity, foulness, or transience of the body**, often contrasting it with the soul or spirit in religious or ascetic contexts:\n\n- **Manusmṛti** (Chapter 6): Describes the body vividly as inherently impure and repulsive—\"This body, which has bones for its pillars, is bound with sinews, plastered with flesh and blood, covered with skin, foul-smelling, and full of urine and feces\"—urging its abandonment for spiritual liberation.[^3]\n\n- **Old English Elegies** (\"Soul and Body II\"): The soul bitterly reproaches the body as a \"flesh-hoard\" and \"filth of the earth,\" a prison of wicked pleasures that leads to hellish torment, emphasizing its degradation and worthlessness after death.[^4]\n\n- **Āṅgirasa Smṛti** (Chapter 1): Refers to the body as transient \"like a bubble of water,\" underscoring its impermanence and lack of enduring value in ethical and ritual contexts.[^5]\n\n- **Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL II** by Charles Dunoyer (Chapter 18): Links personal dignity to bodily cleanliness, portraying filth on the body, clothes, and home as degrading, with hygiene as a virtue advancing human health and beauty.[^6]\n\nThese are primarily Indic (Manusmṛti, Āṅgirasa) and Anglo-Saxon Christian (Elegies) texts disparaging the body to exalt the soul or moral progress. No classical philosophical exaltation of the body's dignity (e.g., as in Stoicism) appears.\n\n[^1]: Charles Dunoyer, *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL I*, [Introduction](/works/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-i-6da8ce/00-introduction/translation/#p-a32ab7).\n\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, [Chapter 12](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/12-de-la-description-des-lois-des-effets-qu-elles-pro/translation/#p-b74497).\n\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 6](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/06/translation/#p-00e87b).\n\n[^4]: *Old English Elegies*, [\"Soul and Body II\"](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/10-soul-and-body-ii/translation/#p-00ea0f).\n\n[^5]: *Āṅgirasa Smṛti*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-6235f0).\n\n[^6]: Charles Dunoyer, *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL II*, [Chapter 18](/works/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-ii-d6ae03/18-viii-application-des-memes-moyens-de-liberte-aux-a/translation/#p-414174).",
